ly Celtic Art in Britain''], Ruth and Vincent Megaw, p.29, accessed 16 August 2010</ref> | |- |[[Mike Morwood]] |27 October 1950 [[Auckland]] – 23 July 2013 |[[University of Auckland]], [[University of New England (Australia)]] | |[[Homo floresiensis]] |- |[[John Mulvaney]] |26 October 1925 – 21 September 2016 |[[Cambridge University]] |"Father of Australian archaeology" | |- |Ken Mulvaney | |University of Western Australia, [[Western Australian Museum]], [[Victoria Archaeological Survey]]<ref>[http://australianarchaeology.com/the-bruce-veitch-award/ken-mulvaney-bv/ Bruce Veitch Award for Excellence in Indigenous Engagement Australian Archaeology Association] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20141206225616/http://australianarchaeology.com/the-bruce-veitch-award/ken-mulvaney-bv/ |date=6 December 2014 }}</ref> |Aboriginal engagement, [[Burrup Peninsula]] rock art | |- |Stephen Munro | |Australian National | |engraved fossil shell from Java<ref>http://au.ibtimes.com/australian-archaeologist-dr-stephen-munro-discovers-earliest-human-engravings-discovered-400000-year</ref> |- |[[Tim Murray (archaeologist)|Tim Murray]] | |[[La Trobe University]], [[University of New South Wales]], [[University of Sydney]], [[Cambridge University]], [[University of Leiden]] [[Université de Paris|Université de Paris I (Panthéon-Sorbonne)]], [[Ecole des hautes etudes en sciences sociales]] (Paris) [[UCL Institute of Archaeology|Institute of Archaeology]], University College London |[[history of archaeology]] | |- |}
